These are returned from the snapshot _status api (examples from 1.x and 2.x) when retrieving the status of a previous snapshot.  It happens to have missing metadata files so it is throwing the exceptions below.

```
{
  "error" : "IndexShardRestoreFailedException[[index_name_3.2017-04][0] failed to read shard snapshot file]; nested: FileNotFoundException[/path_to_index/0/snapshot-index_name_3.2017-04 (No such file or directory)]; ",
  "status" : 500
}
```

```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [ {
      "type" : "index_shard_restore_failed_exception",
      "reason" : "failed to read shard snapshot file",
      "shard" : "0",
      "index" : "index_name_3.2017-04"
    } ],
    "type" : "index_shard_restore_failed_exception",
    "reason" : "failed to read shard snapshot file",
    "shard" : "0",
    "index" : "index_name_3.2017-04",
    "caused_by" : {
      "type" : "no_such_file_exception",
      "reason" : "/path_to_index/0/snapshot-index_name_3.2017-04"
    }
  },
  "status" : 500
}
```

The above exceptions are misleading since it references IndexShardRestoreFailedException and index_shard_restore_failed_exception.  Given that the _status api is only for snapshots (not for snapshot restores), the exception strings can be misleading to the end user.
